The article explores ***the GOP's surrender to Trump*** and the recent endorsements of the former president by prominent Republicans. It:

- Provides the context of **Tom Emmer's withdrawal** from the speaker's race after **Trump's phone call** to rally against him and his previous refusal to endorse Trump.
- Examines the cases of **Steve Scalise** and **Kevin McCarthy**, who also backed Trump after initially distancing themselves from him or challenging his legitimacy.

subCards.title: Actor David Soul, half of 'Starsky & Hutch' duo, dies at 80
subCards.abstract: David Soul has died. The actor, best known as the blond half of crime-fighting duo "Starsky & Hutch" in the popular 1970s television series, was 80.

images.title: Actor David Soul, known for his role in TV series "Starsky & Hutch," has died at 80 years old. Soul, right, is seen here with his co-star Paul Michael Glaser in the long-running series, one of the first of the "New York Cops" series.
images.caption: Actor David Soul, known for his role in TV series "Starsky & Hutch," has died at 80 years old. Soul, right, is seen here with his co-star Paul Michael Glaser in the long-running series, one of the first of the "New York Cops" series.

highlights.text: ***David Soul***, who played the blond half of the crime-fighting duo **"Starsky & Hutch"** in the popular 1970s TV series, **died at 80** on Friday. His wife, Helen Snell, announced his death in a statement, praising his **"extraordinary gifts"** as an actor, singer, storyteller, and friend. Soul starred alongside Paul Michael Glaser as **David Starsky** in the ABC show, which ran from 1975 to 1979 and spawned a host of **children's toys**. He also had a hit single, **"Don't Give Up on Us"**, and performed in several **stage roles** in Britain. In 2001, he won a **libel case** against a journalist who called his play, **"The Dead Monkey"**, the worst production he had ever seen. He and Glaser had cameos in the **2004 big-screen remake** of "Starsky & Hutch", starring Ben Stiller and Owen Wilson.

cards.abstract: North Korea fired over 200 rounds of artillery shells in a disputed sea boundary with South Korea, escalating tensions between the two countries.

images.title: North Korea Artillery Shelling Sparks South's Evacuation Order

topQuestions.q: What was the motive behind North Korea's artillery firing?
How did the 2018 military agreement affect the relations between the two countries?

highlights.text: On ***Nov. 23***, **North Korea** fired more than **200 rounds of artillery shells** near two *South Korean islands* in a **disputed maritime boundary** between the two countries. The firing violated a **fragile military agreement** reached in *2018* between the two rivals and represented a **further escalation** of the tensions. South Korea responded by ordering the **evacuation of its residents** from the islands and conducting **live fire drills** with artillery and tanks in the area. It also **condemned North Korea's actions** as a **provocative act** that **threatens peace** on the Korean peninsula. The two countries' relationship is at one of its **lowest points** in decades, as North Korea withdrew from the agreement only a few months ago. The area is considered a **non-hostility zone** for the two rivals. China, a longtime ally of North Korea, urged the two countries to **"maintain calm and restraint"** and **"refrain from taking actions that aggravate tensions"**.

highlights.text:
The article warns about ***melioidosis***, a **deadly tropical disease** caused by a bacterium, *Burkholderia pseudomallei*, that has recently become **endemic to the southern U.S.**. It provides:

- The historical and current data on **U.S. cases** of melioidosis, which average **12 per year** and are mostly linked to **traveling to tropical or subtropical regions** where the bacterium is present.
- The **symptoms** of melioidosis, which include **fever, joint pain, headaches**, and can lead to **pneumonia, abscesses, and blood infections**.
- The possible **link to climate change**, which could affect the **distribution and spread** of the bacterium and the disease.
- The **advice** from health authorities to **prevent infection** by avoiding contact with **soil or muddy water** after flooding or storms, and by **protecting open wounds** with waterproof dressings, boots, and gloves.
- The **call for awareness** among clinicians to **learn about melioidosis** and to be aware of the **potential for more non-travel cases** as the CDC and state partners continue investigating the **geographic spread** of the bacterium.

cards.title: The Fall of the House of Etsy
cards.abstract: The beloved marketplace is living through a nightmare.

images.title: The Fall of the House of Etsy

topQuestions.q: What can other online marketplaces learn from Etsy's mistakes?

highlights.text:
The article explores ***the fall of Etsy***, a $37 billion online marketplace for handmade and custom-made goods, and analyzes its challenges and problems. It identifies **five reasons** for Etsy's decline:

- **Dropshippers** who act as middlemen and undercut handmade sellers.
- **Counterfeit goods** that constitute a large percentage of products offered and are facilitated by ad words.
- **Small sellers** leaving due to the pandemic and the mandatory opt-ins to advertisements that forced many to pay Etsy a cut.
- **Large sellers** leaving due to the same opt-ins and the lack of quality and customer service that Etsy promised.
- **Etsy is no longer a unique platform** that provides a differentiated and buyer-friendly environment, as similar marketplaces can easily replicate and buy its code.

The article explains how these factors have created a **perverse incentive** for Etsy to grow fast and scale up, but also erode trust and quality among its sellers and consumers. It suggests that Etsy may need to **downscale** its seller network and bring back loyal buyers, or face losing its competitive edge to smaller marketplaces.

cards.title: Yes, there are work-from-home jobs nobody wants
cards.abstract: Work-from-home jobs are often hard to find and highly coveted. But some roles are so unpopular they don't get much interest from job seekers.

images.title: Yes, there are work-from-home jobs nobody wants

topQuestions.q: How do work-from-home jobs nobody wants affect the mental and physical health of workers?

highlights.text:
The article explores ***work-from-home jobs*** that Americans **won't do**, based on a review of open jobs from **Adzuna**, a job-search engine. It identifies **four types of jobs** that are among the least appealing to applicants:

- **Customer support specialist** and **call-center rep**, with average salaries of nearly *$60,000*.
- **Pharmacy tech**, **restaurant host**, and **hotel front desk** staff, with average salaries ranging from *$40,000* to *$50,000*.
- **Merchandiser**, with an average salary of about *$75,000*.

The article explains that some workers, especially **Gen Zers**, prefer jobs that have **an obvious career progression** and offer **flexibility**, **mental-health support**, and **training opportunities**. It also notes that working from home alone is **not a guarantee** of attracting workers, and that some high-skill jobs are usually filled by **job seekers coming to them**. It suggests that employers should be more **thoughtful** about what they offer and how they define their roles, and that workers should be more **flexible** about what they want and how they work.

cards.title: Judge Shuts Down Attempt to Kick Donald Trump Off Ballot
cards.abstract: A bid to get Donald Trump removed from Wyoming's presidential ballot based on the Constitution's 14th Amendment has failed.

images.title: Former president Donald Trump
images.caption: Donald Trump delivering remarks during a campaign rally at the Reno-Sparks Convention Center on December 17, 2023 in Reno, Nevada. An attempt to have Trump removed from the presidential ballot in Wyoming has been rejected in court.

topQuestions.q: How does the 14th Amendment's clause apply to Trump's alleged role in the January 6 riot?
Why did the Wyoming judge dismiss the case without prejudice and what does that mean for future challenges?

highlights.text: The article reports on a ***Wyoming judge's*** decision to **reject a motion** to remove ***Donald Trump*** from the state's **2024 presidential ballot**, based on the **14th Amendment's** clause that bars anyone who participated in an **insurrection** from holding office. The ruling was issued by **Albany County District Court Judge Misha Westby** on **Thursday**, and dismissed the case "without prejudice", meaning it can be refiled. The case was filed by **Tim Newcomb**, a retired attorney, who argued that Trump's alleged role in the **January 6 storming of Congress** constituted an insurrection and made him ineligible to serve a second term. Trump's campaign denied the allegation and said it was a partisan attack on American democracy. The ruling follows similar decisions by **Colorado** and **Maine** courts, which also ruled that Trump was not eligible to be on their primary ballots based on the 14th Amendment. Trump's legal team has appealed both cases to the **Supreme Court**, which could decide the matter on the merits or offer an "off-ramp" for Trump to remain on the ballot.

cards.title: Nearly 17,000 people may have died from hydroxychloroquine: study
cards.abstract: Nearly 17,000 people across six countries may have died because they took hydroxychloroquine (HQC) during the first wave of COVID-19 in 2020, according to a new analysis published by French researchers. highlights.text: A new study by ***French and Canadian researchers*** estimates that **nearly 17,000 people** may have **died** from taking *hydroxychloroquine (HQC)*, an anti-malaria drug, during the first wave of **COVID-19** in 2020. The researchers analyzed data from **six countries** and found an excess of deaths that was likely due to HQC use, despite the lack of evidence of its clinical benefits. They noted that HQC toxicity was partly due to **cardiac side effects** and that the actual number of deaths could be **between 3,000 and 30,000**, depending on the data availability and the region. The study period was from **March to July 2020**, and the drug was widely promoted by former president **Trump** as a possible **"miracle"** treatment.
